bution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Raoul, Yvon.  Spanish Alicia, Andres, Arturo, Beatriz, Elia, Jose, Julio, Miguel, Raul.","French: habitational name from any of numerous places called Chaumont ‘bald mountain’ (ultimately from Latin <i>calvus mons</i>), for example in Cher, Orne, Jura, Haute-Savoie.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Chaumont in Orne (see 1 above)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bègue","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Christophe, Jean Louis.","French (<b>Bègue</b>): nickname for someone afflicted with a stammer, from the Old French adjective <i>besgue</i> ‘having a stammer’ (derived from Middle Dutch <i>beggen</i> ‘to chatter’).","French (<b>Bégué</b> and <b>Begué</b>): variant of <b>Viguié</b>, a status name and occupational name for a judicial officer, from Old French <i>viguier</i> (see   Viger  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Beguin","meanings":["French (also <b>Béguin</b>):","from a diminutive of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bego</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>beg</i>, from Latin <i>beccus</i> ‘beak, bill’.","nickname from <i>beguin</i>, the name for a member of a medieval Christian male religious community (ultimately named after a priest called Lambert le Begue; see   Begue  ) that followed a monastic rule without making perpetual vows and was quickly considered heretic; by extension the term came to mean ‘sanctimonious person’."]},{"name":"Viger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Laurent, Laurette, Lucienne, Marcell, Normand, Pierre, Simonne.","French: status name and occupational name from Old French <i>viguier</i> ‘seigniorial or royal officer responsible for administering justice and collecting state rights’ (from Latin <i>vicarius</i> ‘substitute’).","